title: "Creating images with R"
```{r setup, include=FALSE}
knitr::opts_chunk$set(echo=TRUE, message=FALSE, warning=FALSE, error=FALSE)
Here's my project folder screenshot:
![](project_folder.png)
<div class="bg-box" style="text-align: center;">
and this is [my Github page](https://github.com/ykmhk/stats220)
</div>
## Inspo meme
![](inspo_meme.png)
<div class="bg-box">
This meme is mainly about unexpected punchline, with same scene and same guy smiling awkwardly after checking his computer. The text uses the typical meme style of <span style="font-family: Impact; font-weight:bold; text-transform:uppercase; color:white;">bold, white, all-caps font</span> with a black outline. This makes the text easy to read and visually eye-catching, while also giving the meme a strong and impactful tone.
</div>
## My meme
![](my_meme.png)
<div class="bg-box">
I changed the text from the original “inspo” meme while keeping the same image, adapting it to a programming context where the punchline shows the frustration of fixing bugs.
To enhance the visual impact I changed the font style in the upper half to a lower-case style, which contrasts with the bottom half and emphasizes the initial calm expectation versus the worse outcome in the punchline.
</div>
## My animated meme
![](my_animated_meme.gif)
<div class="bg-box">
For the animated meme, I went further by adding `image_modulate()` to the bottom-half frame, making the image more desaturated and slightly overexposed.
</div>
## Creativity
<div class="bg-box">
For the `{magick}` toolkit, I used text annotation (e.g. `location = "+0-50"`) to fit the text to cover the original text, and `image_crop()` to divide the meme into two halves for animation. I also applied `image_modulate()` to the bottom half to create a more distorted effect, emphasizing the punchline visually.
**Beyond the project requirements**,
I used my own CSS knowledge to customize fonts, colors, borders, and layout, enhancing the overall neatness, readability, and visual appeal of the report.
</div>
## Learning reflection
<div class="bg-box">
One of the important ideas I learned from Module 1 is that tools like HTML, CSS, Markdown, and R can work together to achieve a “1+1>2” effect, creating webpages that are both visually appealing and functional.
I already knew how to write HTML with CSS, but this module taught me a lot, such as getting started with RStudio, which made me even more interested in practical work.
I also realized that it is possible to edit images purely through code using these convenient toolkits, and that Markdown offers a simpler, more user-friendly way to create content compared to HTML.
*Although it feels less flexible than HTML, it is still very convenient.*
Moving forward, I am curious to explore using tools like R to create interactive data visualizations and to learn more about how data-driven reports can dynamically display datasets.
</div>
</div>
